int-org-section.p:
In September 2009 the Commission adopted proposals for the creation of a European Systemic Risk Board (ESRB), which was to monitor and assess risks to the stability of the financial system as a whole; and a European System of Financial Supervisors (ESFS), with the capacity to address recommendations and warnings issued to member states and to the European supervisory authorities. The ESFS comprised three European Supervisory Authorities (ESAs): a Euro­pean Banking Authority; a European Securities and Markets Authority; and a European Insurance and Occupational Pensions Authority, to help rebuild confidence, unify financial rules, resolve problems involving cross-border firms, and prevent the accumulation of risks that could undermine the stability of the financial system. In September 2010 the EP endorsed the new supervisory framework, which was confirmed by ministers responsible for the economy and for finance (the ECOFIN Council) in November. The three ESAs and the ESRB were established in January 2011 to replace the supervisory committees hitherto in place. In December 2012 EU ministers responsible for finance approved plans to deepen and safeguard economic stability through the creation of a banking union (see 
Economic Co-operation
). A Bank Resolution and Recovery Directive (BRRD) was adopted, introducing harmonized procedures for the management of insolvent financial institutions. Member states were required to implement the Directive by the end of 2014 (however, 11 states failed to do so).

In May 2014 the European Commission published an initial comprehensive review of its financial regulation framework, following the proposal of more than 40 reform measures in the wake of the economic and financial crisis in the eurozone. In November 2016 the Commission proposed a number of amendments to the CRD, as part of a package of legislative measures that also sought to amend the Capital Requirements Regulation, the BRRD and the Single Resolution Mechanism Regulation (see 
Economic Co-operation
), in order to address structural weaknesses and further bolster the European economy.
